This is an example of a channel packed mask. The R, G and B channels are "extracted" into their own masks. Alternately, you can feed in your own single-channel masks, or generate your own on the fly.

Here, I am using the AYS noise scheduler, although, I typically use karras.

AYS distributes noise more evenly throughout the diffusion process than Karras, which distributes higher noise in earlier steps, and less in latter steps.

Note: this may be slightly more noticeable when using ipAdapters or controlNets with end-at-step settings.

I have found both schedulers very good and very similar. YMMV.

Note: Randomly selects an input image from a filtered list, and each is attention masked by its respective mask channels, (combined with prompt conditioning masks). Also using a high style weighting factor here, and have enabled "expand style" to draw in the style further.
Select a preset style from the Prompt Styler node. For those unfamiliar, these act like "Prompt Expanders" - adding more information to your initial prompts.
Note that the prompt guidance is quite minimal, as I am leaning more into the information contained in the ipAdapters to drive the final look.

The main base resolutions I typically generate at are: 896*1152, 1344*768 and 1536*640 - however - since falling in love with "hi-res UNfix" i typically multiply these numbers by 2 (or 3) to "unshrink" and tease out more "ai-ness" from the images.
